@node "Use" "Usage"
                     **************************************
                     *                USAGE               *
                     **************************************


 To use WordPad is very easy all buttons are self-explanatory, but heres a
brief run-through.



 Main Toolbar:

     New - This clears all text in the editor window.

     Open - Allows you to open an existing text file.

     Save - Allows you to save your text.

     Print - This will print the current text in the editor window.

     Cut - Deletes the selected text into the clip board.

     Copy - copies the selected text into the clipboard

     Paste - Brings the contents of the clipboard into the editor window


 Format Toolbar:

     B - Makes the text Bold

     I - Makes the Text Italic

     U - Makes the text Underlined


****************************************** * Using the NEW Multiple Document
support* ******************************************


Loading a new one: -----------------

     To load a new document, click 'Open' in the toolbar
     or 'Open' in the menu, select the deired file.

     When you click 'Ok' on the requester the documents
     name will appear in the document tree and will be
     ready for editing. you can switch to any other
     document in the tree without losing any the document
     or any changes made to it.


Switch between dcouments ------------------------

     You can edit another document be double clicking on the
     documents name in the document tree, its text will then
     appear in the editor.



Removing Documents. -------------------
     Click on the one you want removed and select
     'Remove' from the menu. You will be asked if you
     want to save it if the file has been modified.

Saving a document. -----------------
     Again click on the document in the tree. then
     click save or save as in the toolbar or menu.

Adding a document to the favourites list:
    Select  the document you want to add, then
    click "Add To Favourites" above the tree.


@endnode

